<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-04-27T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-04-27T11:00:00-05:00" n="336" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">875.01/192: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Child</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-04-27T17:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">April 27,
                                        1922—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 28—12:24
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>66. Your 52 April 24, 4 p.m. The powers in the Supreme Council have
                            recognized Albania <hi rend="italic">de jure</hi>. Of these powers
                            England and Italy have sent Ministers. France is represented only by a
                            consul at Scutari. Japan has no representative. The other countries
                            which have accorded <hi rend="italic">de jure</hi> recognition are
                            Finland, Switzerland, Belgium and Jugoslavia and of these only
                            Jugoslavia is represented, having a Chargé d’Affaires.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Child</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>